    {
      "file": "alex-bunardzic.json",
      "udtType": "Member",
      "id": "alex-bunardzic",
      "body": {
        "udtType": "Member",
        "parameters": {
          "name": "Alex Bunardzic",
          "role": "founding member",
          "title": "Business Velocity Architect, Experienced Software Philosopher",
          "bio": "Alex is the founder of the Guild and one of its clearest voices on sustainable software delivery, business flexibility, and small-step engineering discipline.\n\nFounder\nSoftware Development Since 1990\nAI Craftspeople Guild\n\n## Alex Bunardzic\n\nBusiness Velocity Architect, Experienced Software Philosopher\n\nBusiness Velocity Architect, Experienced Software Philosopher. TDD, mutation testing, shift-left, service virtualization, CI/CD, TBD\n\nTDD\nMutation Testing\nShift-Left\nService Virtualization\nCI/CD\nBusiness Velocity\n\nAlex has been doing software development since 1990. His professional passion is bringing soft into software. Which means software must be soft, maleable, pliable. That quality enables the flexibility of the business operations.\n\nIn order to make sure that software we are building is flexible, we must evolve it one step at a time. Each step (and the smaller that step is, the better) must get verified by automated testing. Early failures are welcome, because they are small and they force us to fix them right away. In the software engineering discipline, giant steps are foolish steps. It is more prudent to stay with small steps (many, many small steps) on our journey to deliver value to customer satisfaction.\n\n**Move fast to delight customers!**\n\n[Visit me and see how I can improve your success!](https://alexbunardzic.com/)",
          "avatar_href": "Alex3D.jpg",
          "expertise_tags": [
            "TDD",
            "Mutation Testing",
            "Shift-Left",
            "Service Virtualization",
            "CI/CD",
            "Business Velocity"
          ],
          "links": {},
          "joined_date": ""
        },
        "tags": {
          "id": "alex-bunardzic",
          "slug": "alex-bunardzic",
          "paper_ids": [],
          "instance_path": "udts/instances/alex-bunardzic.json",
          "ingested_at": "2026-04-17T20:08:45Z",
          "schema_version": "1.0.0"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "file": "jona-heidsick.json",
      "udtType": "Member",
      "id": "jona-heidsick",
      "body": {
        "udtType": "Member",
        "parameters": {
          "name": "Jona Heidsick",
          "role": "founding member",
          "title": "Full-Stack Architect · First-Principles Architect",
          "bio": "Jona's work sits at the intersection of first-principles architecture, clean code, protocol design, and agentic AI systems built on classical engineering foundations.\n\nFounding Member\nFull-Stack Architect\nFirst-Principles Architect\n25 Years Building & Operating Software Systems\n\n## Jona Heidsick\n\nFounding Member · Full-Stack Software Engineer · 25 Years Building & Operating Software Systems\n\nFounding Member · Full-Stack Architect · First-Principles Architect\n\nI've been writing, shipping, and running software for 25 years. Full stack, from bare metal to frontend, across industries. The constant through all of it: strip the problem to its essential structure, build the minimum that actually works, then iterate. First-principles thinking, minimum viable architecture, Occam's Razor as engineering discipline.\n\nI have a borderline obsession with clean code and a deep affinity for functional and declarative programming - immutability, composition, expressing *what* over *how*, and explicitness over magic. These aren't aesthetic preferences; they're how you keep systems honest at scale.\n\nToday I focus on agentic AI systems, MCP integrations, and backend reliability - built on classical foundations: DDD, TDD, and continuous delivery. I was an early MCP adopter and have built multiple protocol servers. I've also worked extensively in blockchain (Algorand, NEAR, Cardano).\n\nA recurring theme in my work is what I call \"hacking the coding process itself\" - engineering not just the product, but the way it's made. I think of AI through the lens of Extended Mind Theory: it extends the engineer's cognition, it doesn't replace it. That distinction matters when you're drawing lines around responsibility, authorship, and failure.\n\nI co-authored and signed the ACG manifesto because craft needs defending - especially now, when the tools are powerful enough to make sloppiness scale.\n\nFirst-Principles\nMCP\nAgentic AI\nDDD/TDD\nContinuous Delivery\nBlockchain\nClean Code\nFunctional Programming\nDeclarative Programming\nExtended Mind Theory",
          "avatar_href": "Jona.png",
          "expertise_tags": [
            "First-Principles",
            "MCP",
            "Agentic AI",
            "DDD/TDD",
            "Continuous Delivery",
            "Blockchain",
            "Clean Code",
            "Functional Programming",
            "Declarative Programming",
            "Extended Mind Theory"
          ],
          "links": {},
          "joined_date": ""
        },
        "tags": {
          "id": "jona-heidsick",
          "slug": "jona-heidsick",
          "paper_ids": [],
          "instance_path": "udts/instances/jona-heidsick.json",
          "ingested_at": "2026-04-17T20:08:45Z",
